---
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const title = "February 2026: catching up, celebrating love, and being very very very active";
export const date = "2026-03-02";
export const excerpt =
  "Two weeks in New York, a brother's engagement, a best friend's wedding, and my most active month in recent memory.";
export const tags = ["new-york", "seattle", "february-2026", "intentional-living"];
---

<SiteLayout title={`${title} — Saachi K Gupta`}>
  <h1>{title}</h1>
  <p style="opacity:0.7;">{date}</p>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    February was a month of catching up with friends, celebrating love, and being very very very active.
  </p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 28px;">Snoqualmie + meeting Gus</h2>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    I started the month in Seattle, skiing at Snoqualmie — and had the privilege of meeting Gus, the GM of the mountain.
    He chatted with me about his career, the nitty gritty of running a ski resort, and gave me a lot to think about:
    the operational rigor and capital allocation questions inherent in building something joyful, delightful, and sustainable.
  </p>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    It was also a callback to one of the best classes I took at Wharton — The Business of Water — applied in real life,
    as Snoqualmie navigates permitting, water rights, and the conservation mandates inherent in a climate-dependent business.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/catamount.JPEG" alt="Skiing selfie on the slopes" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
  </figure>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 28px;">Two weeks in New York</h2>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    Then: two weeks in New York, bookended by celebrating my favorite people. My brother got engaged to his longtime
    girlfriend — proving that you CAN find love at UChicago. My best friend from UChicago (who I followed to Wharton) got married.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/champagne.JPEG" alt="Champagne tower for a celebration" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
    <figcaption>The champagne tower said it all.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    In between, I spent time in the city catching up with friends from undergrad, high school, business school,
    past jobs, and my family friends and cousins. New York has a way of making every chapter of your life feel simultaneous.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/IMG_3135.JPEG" alt="Catching up with a friend in New York" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/wburb.JPEG" alt="Walking in Williamsburg with the NYC skyline behind us" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
    <figcaption>Williamsburg walks with the Manhattan skyline. One of my favorite views.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    Three years out of business school, I — and so many of my friends — are at a point of reflection and re-evaluation.
    Jobs, cities, relationships. The pull of being near family and finding joy at work is stronger now.
    We've been back in the real world long enough to know what we actually want from it.
  </p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 28px;">Most active month in recent memory</h2>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    February was also my most active month in recent memory. Spurred by my Q1 Bingo, I walked to new parks,
    went swimming, made plans to ski, and ended the month having moved my body in some form every single day.
  </p>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    It brought me back to Managerial Decision Making with Katy Milkman at Wharton — we went deep into habit formation,
    and what actually makes behavior stick. My two-week lifting streak in Williamsburg?
    Entirely sustained by knowing my cousin would be there every morning waiting for me.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/Attachment-2.png" alt="Strava February totals: 28 days, 36 hours, 91.2 miles, 8,347 ft elevation" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
    <figcaption>28 days. Every single one.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/Attachment-1.png" alt="Strava top sports breakdown: 57% running, 31% weightlifting, 6% skiing, 6% swimming" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/Attachment-3.png" alt="Strava February 2026 activity hours compared to past months — February highlighted as second highest" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
    <figcaption>February 2026 was my second most active month in the past year. I'll take it.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <figure>
    <img src="/images/swim.JPEG" alt="Swim gear and workout printout at the pool" style="max-width: 420px; width: 100%; border-radius: 10px;" />
    <figcaption>Back in the pool. Brought a printed workout set and everything.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 28px;">How the month ended</h2>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    The month ended strong: a large group dinner at my favorite restaurant, Homer, to celebrate my friend Hannah's
    return from her sabbatical; a day-trip to Bainbridge Island with Hannah — ferry ride, long walk, beautiful light;
    and a Seattle Torrent PWHL game featuring FOUR Team USA Olympians, including Hillary Knight.
    I left that arena very, very happy.
  </p>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    I feel beyond lucky for the community I have on both coasts.
  </p>

  <h2 style="margin-top: 28px;">March is about intention</h2>

  <p style="max-width: 75ch;">
    Intentional time with the people I love — not just when geography makes it easy, but making the actual ask and showing up.
    Getting back on my bike and back into Seattle's public pools, after too much time away from both.
    And DEFINITELY getting to see the tulips in the Skagit Valley — some things are non-negotiable.
  </p>
</SiteLayout>
